==English==
===Etymology===
The English word "Hubbub" first appeared in print with a description of the Ic[h]thiophagi, a tribe of fish-eating Africans who wore their heads beneath their shoulders when they would "''flocke together to go drincke ...shouting as they go with an yrishe whobub''".<1>

In [[The Faerie Queen]], [[Edmund Spenser]] drew on his observations of warfare in the Irish province of Munster to describe, "''a noyse of many bagpipes shrill, and shrieking hububs them approaching nere''"; after that, in [[A View of the Present State of Ireland]], he described, "''the [[Scythian]]s and [[Parthian]]s coming to give the charge at battles: at which it is said, that they came running with a terrible yell as if heaven and earth would have gone together, which is the very image of the Irish hubub, which their [[kern]] use at their first encounter''."

After Spenser came the outrage of Autolycus, a cut-purse rogue in Shakespeare's [[The Winter's Tale]] who was thwarted in the market place by the "''whoo-bub''" of a meddling father. At about the same time, the word appeared in the works of [[Barnaby Rich]], an English soldier in Ireland for forty years who served the crown with christian vigour. A strong protestant, he was also a great man for pamphleteering, and managed the trick of informing two of Shakespeare's comedies - [[The Merry Wives of Windsor]] and [[Measure for Measure]] - while agitating his own readers against the "''inhuman loathsomenes''" of the natives of his adopted land. The modern spelling of the word was fixed in the title of his late satire, [[The Irish Hubbub]], published in 1617 as the author's final blast against the world.

After that came [[Milton]] with his description in [[Paradise Lost]] of the noise first heard by [[Satan]] on entering the Abyss:

    At length a universal hubbub wild
    Of stunning sounds and voices all confused,
    Borne through the hollow dark, assaults his ear
    With loudest vehemence.

By then the word had been established, and beyond Ireland (and Icthiophagia) it was being invoked by the colonists of Virginia and New England in their peculiar struggles.

In english etymology it is reckoned that ''Hubbub'' represents something Irish, the origin lying in the gaelic ''Abú!'' the assumed war-cry of the ancients, or ''Ub!'' a cry of aversion or contempt. But another authority has rejected utterly the connection with ''Abú'', and accepts strong evidence for a derivation from the gaelic ''Ob!'' a cry of surprise.<2>

The dispute goes on, but the current understanding seems to be that ''Hubbub'' (or ''whobub'', ''whoo-bub'', ''whoopubb'', ''hubub(b)'' or ''hobou'') derives from a gaelic cry of surprise or contempt or sorrow or aversion, or a howling lamentation or war-cry, or the clamour of boozers, or the rage of a daughter's father, or the din of pandaemonium.


   1. ^ The quote - cited in the OED - is from the 1555 edition of ''Fardle Facions'' by W.Watreman. See [[Diodorus Siculus]] for the Ichthyphagi of the Red Sea shore.
   2. ^ This alternative view comes from David Greene in ''The Irish War-Cry'' Eriu (1966) pp.167-173; Greene was a difficult scholar, and went on in the same paper to upset nationalist assumptions in Ireland with his argument that the war-cry abú (familiar from slogans and chants of the romantic gaelic revival) derives not from old-irish, but from middle-english by way of the 12th century Cambro-Norman invasion of Ireland. See also Eric Partridge ''Origins: A Short Etymological Dictionary of Modern English'' 4th ed.(London 1966) p.298 for a similar derivation of Hubbub.

